(
  Example G-Code demonstrating HttpCommand usage with http_settings.json
  
  This file shows how to use predefined tokens and commands stored in
  /localfs/http_settings.json to make HTTP requests during CNC operations.
  
  Place this example alongside http_settings.json in the example_configs/ directory.
)

(========================)
( SIMPLE COMMAND USAGE   )
(========================)

(Fetch temperature from a sensor server using a predefined command)
$HTTP/Command=@fetch_temperature
o100 if [#<_HTTP_STATUS> NE 200]
  M118 Error fetching temperature: #<_HTTP_STATUS>
  M0 (Sensor unreachable)
o100 endif

(Fetch humidity using another predefined command)
$HTTP/Command=@fetch_humidity
M118 Humidity: #<_HTTP_RESPONSE_LEN> bytes received

(========================)
(  TOKEN SUBSTITUTION    )
(========================)

(Use a token in headers for Home Assistant API call)
(Token: ${ha_token} is a Bearer token stored in http_settings.json)
$HTTP/Command=@ha_get_room_temp
#<room_temperature> = #<_room_temp>
M118 Room temperature from Home Assistant: #<room_temperature>°C

(Trigger a Home Assistant automation when job completes)
(Uses multiple tokens and custom headers)
$HTTP/Command=@ha_call_automation
o200 if [#<_HTTP_STATUS> GE 200] AND [#<_HTTP_STATUS> LT 300]
  M118 Successfully logged to Home Assistant
o200 else
  M118 Home Assistant API error: #<_HTTP_STATUS>
o200 endif

(========================)
( MULTIPLE EXTRACTIONS  )
(========================)

(Fetch multiple sensor readings in a single request)
(Extracts temperature, humidity, and pressure into separate parameters)
$HTTP/Command=@fetch_all_sensors
M118 Temperature: #<_temperature>°C
M118 Humidity: #<_humidity>%
M118 Pressure: #<_pressure> hPa

(Check if conditions are safe to proceed)
o300 if [#<_temperature> GT 35]
  M118 WARNING: Temperature too high!
  M0 (Cool down before continuing)
o300 endif

(========================)
( WEBHOOK LOGGING       )
(========================)

(Log job start to a webhook service)
(Sends JSON with event name and timestamp)
(Note: Timestamp is hardcoded in this example; could be parameterized)
$HTTP/Command=@webhook_log_start
o400 if [#<_HTTP_STATUS> EQ 200]
  M118 Job start logged
o400 endif

(... perform CNC operations here ...)
G0 X0 Y0 Z0
G1 X10 Y10 F100

(Log job completion)
$HTTP/Command=@webhook_log_complete
o500 if [#<_HTTP_STATUS> EQ 200]
  M118 Job completion logged
o500 endif

(========================)
( ERROR HANDLING        )
(========================)

(Example: Check if a backend service is healthy before starting)
$HTTP/Command=@check_system_health
#<cpu_load> = #<_cpu_usage>
#<memory_free> = #<_memory_available>

o600 if [#<cpu_load> GT 80]
  M118 System CPU too high: #<_cpu_usage>%
  M0 (Wait for system to cool down)
o600 endif

o700 if [#<memory_free> LT 100]
  M118 Low memory available: #<_memory_available> MB
  M0 (Close other applications)
o700 endif

(========================)
( GET NEXT JOB          )
(========================)

(Retrieve job details from a queuing system)
(Extracts job ID and part count)
$HTTP/Command=@get_next_job
#<job_id> = #<_job_id>
#<parts_to_produce> = #<_part_count>

M118 Starting job #<job_id>
M118 Parts to produce: #<parts_to_produce>

(Use extracted values in operations)
G91 (Relative positioning)
o800 repeat [#<_part_count>]
  (... produce one part ...)
  G1 X1 Y1 Z1 F50
o800 endrepeat

(========================)
( METRICS SUBMISSION    )
(========================)

(Submit job metrics to Prometheus/metrics system)
(Includes job duration and parts produced data)
$HTTP/Command=@post_job_metrics
o900 if [#<_HTTP_STATUS> EQ 200]
  M118 Metrics submitted successfully
o900 else
  M118 Failed to submit metrics
o900 endif

(========================)
( DATABASE SUBMISSION   )
(========================)

(Submit machine data to InfluxDB using token substitution)
(Token ${influx_token} is used in the Authorization header)
$HTTP/Command=@post_to_influxdb
M118 Machine metrics recorded

(========================)
( TIMEOUT HANDLING      )
(========================)

(Query Prometheus with a 5-second timeout)
(Extracts uptime data from a complex JSON response)
$HTTP/Command=@query_prometheus
o1000 if [#<_HTTP_STATUS> EQ 200]
  M118 System uptime: #<_uptime_seconds> seconds
o1000 else
  M118 Prometheus query timed out or failed
o1000 endif

(========================)
( DIFFERENT HTTP METHODS)
(========================)

(PUT request - Update job status)
$HTTP/Command=@put_job_status
M118 Job status updated to running (45% progress)

(DELETE request - Clean up old logs)
$HTTP/Command=@delete_old_logs
o1100 if [#<_HTTP_STATUS> EQ 204]
  M118 Old logs deleted
o1100 endif

(========================)
( FETCH TOOL OFFSETS    )
(========================)

(Get current tool offsets from tool management system)
(Useful for tool changer systems or multi-tool operations)
$HTTP/Command=@fetch_tool_offsets
#<z_offset> = #<_tool_z_offset>
#<tool_diam> = #<_tool_diameter>

M118 Tool Z Offset: #<z_offset>
M118 Tool Diameter: #<tool_diam>

(Apply tool offset)
G43 H1 (Apply compensation using fetched data)

(========================)
( END OF EXAMPLE        )
(========================)

M118 All HTTP examples completed!
M5 (Stop spindle)
G0 Z10 (Move to safe height)

(End of job)
G0 X0 Y0 (Return to origin)
M30 (Program end)
